{"title_page": "Battle of the Anio River (361 BC)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|image=File:Hubert Robert, The Ponte Salario, c. 1775, NGA 41665.jpg\n|caption=An 18th century depiction of the [[Ponte Salario]], the point at which the [[Via Salaria]] crosses over the [[Anio River]]\n|conflict=Battle of the Anio River\n|partof=[[Roman-Gallic Wars]]\n|date=361 BC\n|place=[[Via Salaria]] and [[Anio River]], [[Italy]]\n|result=Roman victory\n|combatant2=[[Gaul]]s\n|combatant1=[[File:Vexilloid of the Roman Empire.svg|21px]] [[Roman Republic]]\n|commander1=[[Titus Quinctius Pennus Capitolinus Crispinus]]\n|commander2=\n|strength1=Unknown\n|strength2=Unknown\n|casualties1=Unknown\n|casualties2=Unknown\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Roman-Gaulish Wars}}\n\nThe '''Battle of the Anio River''' was fought in 361 BC between the [[Roman Republic]], led by the dictator [[Titus Quinctius Pennus Capitolinus Crispinus]], and a group of [[Gaul]]s who had encamped near the [[Via Salaria]] beyond the bridge over the [[Anio River]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/986030771|title=Roman Republic at War : a Compendium of Roman Battles from 502 to 31 BC.|last=Taylor, Don.|date=2017|publisher=Pen and Sword|isbn=978-1-4738-9444-0|oclc=986030771}}</ref>\n== Background == \n[[Titus Quinctius Pennus Capitolinus Crispinus]] was appointed [[roman dictator|dictator]] in 361 BC, most likely due to the presence of [[Gaul]]s and their proximity to Rome.  They had encamped on the side of the [[Anio River]] farthest from the city near the [[Via Salaria]], roughly 3 km north of the [[Colline Gate]].  Upon being appointed dictator, Crispinus ordered that the courts be suspended and that all men of military qualifications join him to march north to the river.  The army then encamped on the side of the river opposite the Gauls.<ref>[[Livy]], [[Ab Urbe Condita Libri|''Ab Urbe Condita'']] 7.9</ref>\n\n== Battle ==\nSkirmishing began over possession of the bridge that crossed the river, but it yielded no results as both sides were evenly matched.  It continued on until a large Gaul came to the bridge, demanding that the Romans send their bravest man to fight him so that the standoff could be resolved.<ref>Livy, ''Ab Urbe Condita'' 7.9</ref> The Romans did not respond to his requests until [[Titus Manlius Imperiosus Torquatus]] approached the dictator and volunteered himself.  He confronted the Gaul, who was much larger and more well-armed than he.  Manlius managed to parry of the Gaul's strokes.  He exploited the Gaul's size and snuck between his sword and body, leaving himself unexposed and delivering a decisive blow to his groin and stomach, killing his enemy and therefore deciding the result of the battle.<ref>Livy, ''Ab Urbe Condita'' 7.10</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nManlius was given the honorary [[cognomen]] [[wikt:torquatus|\"Torquatus\"]], meaning \"adorned with a neck chain or collar,\" a reference to the chain which was borne by the Gaul whom Manlius killed.<ref>Livy, ''Ab Urbe Condita'' 7.10</ref>  The Gauls retreated east from the bridge to the town of [[Tibur]], where they formed a military alliance with the Tiburtes, who provided them with supplies.  From there, they entered [[Campania]].<ref>Livy, ''Ab Urbe Condita'' 7.11</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Italy}}\n\n[[Category:360s BC conflicts]]\n[[Category:4th century BC in the Roman Republic]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Roman Republic]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Gauls]]\n[[Category:Battles in Lazio]]\n[[Category:History of Lazio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|image=File:Hubert Robert, The Ponte Salario, c. 1775, NGA 41665.jpg\n|caption=An 18th century depiction of the [[Ponte Salario]], the point at which the [[Via Salaria]] crosses over the [[Anio River]]\n|conflict=Battle of the Anio River\n|partof=Roman-Gaulish Wars\n|date=361 BC\n|place=[[Via Salaria]] and [[Anio River]], [[Italy]]\n|result=Roman victory\n|combatant2=[[Gaul]]s\n|combatant1=[[File:Vexilloid of the Roman Empire.svg|21px]] [[Roman Republic]]\n|commander1=[[Titus Quinctius Pennus Capitolinus Crispinus]]\n|commander2=\n|strength1=Unknown\n|strength2=Unknown\n|casualties1=Unknown\n|casualties2=Unknown\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Roman-Gaulish Wars}}\n\nThe '''Battle of the Anio River''' was fought in 361 BC between the [[Roman Republic]], led by the dictator [[Titus Quinctius Pennus Capitolinus Crispinus]], and a group of [[Gaul]]s who had encamped near the [[Via Salaria]] beyond the bridge over the [[Anio River]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/986030771|title=Roman Republic at War : a Compendium of Roman Battles from 502 to 31 BC.|last=Taylor, Don.|date=2017|publisher=Pen and Sword|isbn=978-1-4738-9444-0|oclc=986030771}}</ref>\n== Background == \n[[Titus Quinctius Pennus Capitolinus Crispinus]] was appointed [[roman dictator|dictator]] in 361 BC, most likely due to the presence of [[Gaul]]s and their proximity to Rome.  They had encamped on the side of the [[Anio River]] farthest from the city near the [[Via Salaria]], roughly 3 km north of the [[Colline Gate]].  Upon being appointed dictator, Crispinus ordered that the courts be suspended and that all men of military qualifications join him to march north to the river.  The army then encamped on the side of the river opposite the Gauls.<ref>[[Livy]], [[Ab Urbe Condita Libri|''Ab Urbe Condita'']] 7.9</ref>\n\n== Battle ==\nSkirmishing began over possession of the bridge that crossed the river, but it yielded no results as both sides were evenly matched.  It continued on until a large Gaul came to the bridge, demanding that the Romans send their bravest man to fight him so that the standoff could be resolved.<ref>Livy, ''Ab Urbe Condita'' 7.9</ref> The Romans did not respond to his requests until [[Titus Manlius Imperiosus Torquatus]] approached the dictator and volunteered himself.  He confronted the Gaul, who was much larger and more well-armed than he.  Manlius managed to parry of the Gaul's strokes.  He exploited the Gaul's size and snuck between his sword and body, leaving himself unexposed and delivering a decisive blow to his groin and stomach, killing his enemy and therefore deciding the result of the battle.<ref>Livy, ''Ab Urbe Condita'' 7.10</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nManlius was given the honorary [[cognomen]] [[wikt:torquatus|\"Torquatus\"]], meaning \"adorned with a neck chain or collar,\" a reference to the chain which was borne by the Gaul whom Manlius killed.<ref>Livy, ''Ab Urbe Condita'' 7.10</ref>  The Gauls retreated east from the bridge to the town of [[Tibur]], where they formed a military alliance with the Tiburtes, who provided them with supplies.  From there, they entered [[Campania]].<ref>Livy, ''Ab Urbe Condita'' 7.11</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Italy}}\n\n[[Category:360s BC conflicts]]\n[[Category:4th century BC in the Roman Republic]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Roman Republic]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Gauls]]\n[[Category:Battles in Lazio]]\n[[Category:History of Lazio]]\n", "name_user": "Holodwig21", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_the_Anio_River_(361_BC)"}
